    <item>
      <title>Post-fire impacts on hydrological and land-surface processes</title>
      <link>https://mountain-hydrology.github.io/project/wildfire/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Aug 2022 11:25:57 -0600</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mountain-hydrology.github.io/project/wildfire/</guid>
      <description>&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;th&gt;PI&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;th&gt;Siwei He&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Organization&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;NOAA Global Systems Laboratory&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Period&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;2022-08 to 2023-01&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, the impact of wildfires on the land-surface biogeophysical properties, such as soil
hydraulic conductivity and vegetation type, was identified and parameterized.
Then, the impact of post-wildfire conditions on weather forecasting was investigated
by considering post-wildfire land-surface conditions in the Weather Research and Forecasting (WRF) model.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
